Bill Dobbins On Photography
About photographic history, style, equipment, techniques by pro photographer Bill Dobbins
Uncategorized
MARILYN MONROE: THE GREATEST MODEL?
Date: November 16, 2016Author: billdobbins 0 Comments   
MARILYN MONROE: THE GREATEST MODEL?
The Camera Loved Her Like Nobody Else
By Bill Dobbins
http://www.billdobbinsphotography.com
What sets Marilyn Monroe apart is not just her beauty but her uncanny ability to communicate emotion and personality in her facial expressions. And those expressions could change almost faster than the photographer could press the shutter release.
There is no doubt that Marilyn Monroe has become one of the major iconic figures in our celebrate-oriented world. As time goes on her celebrity seems to grow rather than diminish. Not her status as a movie star necessarily, although she was undoubtedly successful as a film star. Her films are still viewed on cable and services like Netflix and her ability as an actress is recognized. But Marilyn was no Meryl Streep. It is more her attractive, physical presence in movie and her ability to project the persona of âMarilynâ that continues to fascinate.
Her evolution from the young Norma Jean Mortensen Baker to the world famous Marilyn Monroe involved quite a journey. She spent most of her childhood in foster homes and an orphanage and married at age 16, no doubt to try and establish some kind of a normal life outside of the âsystem.â This may also somewhat explain why she seemed to insecure and needy throughout her career â exhibiting a kind of vulnerability that was a large part of her sexual appeal.
Before she was the blond bombshell, Norma Jeane Baker was already a highly attractive, sexy and accomplished model.
Photographer Andre de Dienes began shooting her as Norma Jean and continued to photograph Marilyn Monroe almost to the end of her life.
One of the most iconic of photos â Marilyn over a subway grating in the movie The Seven Year Itch. Photo by Gary Winogrand.
Marilyn Monroe was constantly featured on covers like this for one Life Magazine.
Norma Jeane began modeling in 1944, signed a couple of short-lived contracts with movie studios in the late 1940s but her career really took off when she signed with Fox in 1951. Soon she was one of the most bankable stars in the industry and during her short 10 year career as an actress her movies grossed some $200 million (equivalent to many times that in todayâs dollars).
But while Marilynâs movies still have an audience, it is her still photos that continue to make her so relevant. There have been few models in history whom the camera seemed to love so much. I first became aware of this when I saw a documentary in which four photographers talked about their experiences shooting MM. They all agreed that her face was so expressive that it was almost impossible to shoot the same photo of her twice. She would look sexy, sad, angry, pouting, fearful and so forth with one expression following the other in rapid order. All a photographer had to do was keep shooting and try to capture the magic.
Marilyn at her most endearing as the worldly but innocent star of the movie Bus Stop.
Marilyn was beautiful and sexy but she was able to manifest personality like almost nobody else. The ability to express on the face the thoughts and feelings going through the mind is a hallmark of particularly talented actors and models. And Marilyn Monroe was incredible when it came to this ability. This is why she was able to take the character of the âdumb blondeâ and give it a dimension no actress had ever achieve before. The dumb blonde persona appeals to men because she appears vulnerable and submissive, totally non-threatening. But watch Marilyn in a movie like Bus Stop and she comes across as endearingly innocent while also worldly and experienced. Men want to sleep with a character like this but also protect and take care of her.
With Marilyn Monroe you saw the dumb blonde evolve in the more impressive âblond bombshell.â Still dumb for the most part, but larger than life and much more emotionally complex in her appeal.
Mae West was definitely a blond bombshell but as a witty, accomplished playwright, was a long way from a dumb blonde. Is that a pistol in our pocket or are we just glad to see her?
Jean Harlow was almost the prototype of the movie character as sexy, dumb blonde. Photo by George Hurrell
Diana Dors had some success as a Marilyn clone â and no doubt sold a lot of push up bras
Mamie Van Doren was another of the actresses recruited by various studios to try and emulate the success of Marilyn Monroe.
There have been other blond bombshells before and since. Jean Harlow was one of the best. No Shakespearean actress, but a wonderful movie star whose personality and sexuality exploded off the screen. Once Marilyn was on the scene, she inspired a lot of imitators. Such as English actress Diana Dors, a walking advertisement for the tight sweater and uplift bra. And Mamie Van Doren, another actress with ample curves who was groomed to be the new Marilyn with only marginal success.
The one Marilyn-clone who really did achieve some success was Jane Mansfield. She was gorgeous, with a spectacular figure and a definite talent for light comedy. But she limited herself by developing an almost comic-book bombshell persona that restricted the kind of roles she would succeed in. Unfortunately for her, when Marilyn died Mansfieldâs career mostly died with it.
Jane Mansfield was one of the more successful of the actresses spawned by the success of Marilyn Monroe. She Marilyn died, the same thing pretty much happened to Mansfieldâs success â followed unfortunately by an early death.
Loni Anderson was chosen for WKRP in Cincinnati in part because of her resemblance to Jane Mansfield. She went on to have a successful career doing light comedy on television â and married Burt Reynolds.
A more modern counterpart to Jane Mansfield is Loni Anderson who had a successful run in WLRP in Cincinnati. She had a similar appeal to Mansfield but her on-screen persona was smarter, more controlled and less over-the-top so she has had a longer and more varied success as an actress.
But none of these women had the acting talent of Marilyn Monroe and none anywhere near her ability as a model. Marilyn was able to shoot with many of the best photographers in the world because she was so famous and also such a great model. For example, she formed an ongoing professional relationship with photographer Milton Green that resulted in a number of her most memorable photographs.
Unlike the MM wannabes. Marilyn had a serious and successful movie career, such as starring in The Misfits with Montgomery Clift and Clark Gable, directed by John Huston and written by husband Arthur Miller.
Of course, as Norma Jeane she was very much in demand as pin-up model. Hungarian-Romanian photographer Andre de Dienes began photographing her when she was 19 years old and continued to work with her off and on until just before her death. In his work we see both the fresh-faced and innocent Norma Jeane and the somewhat tired and worn Marilyn near the end of her life. He also had a romantic relationship with his model and published a book of photos and a memoire focused on their time together called Marilyn Mon Amour.
Photographer Andre de Dienes had a long relationship, both professional and personal, with Norma Jeane Baker and then Marilyn Monroe â and published this book about it.
Of course, Marilynâs fame was accelerated when she posed nude for a calendar in 1955, and Hugh Hefner published a photo from that session as the centerfold in the first issue of Playboy.
Marilyn Monroe was tremendously ambitious as an actress, attending the Actorâs Studio in New York and as an intellectual, eventually marrying playwright Arthur Miller. She also married baseball star Joe DiMaggio, a relationship which generated one story i am fond of. Marilyn made an appearance in Time Square surrounded by thousands of cheering fans. She went back home and told DiMaggio how exciting it had been. âYou have no idea!â she exclaimed. DiMaggio, who was one of the most famous athletes of all time and was accustomed to adoring cheers from a sold-out Yankee Stadium, is supposed to have replied simply, âYes, I do.â
At Grummanâs Chinese Theater to make imprints of their hands and feet, Marilyn is supposed to have said to Jane Russell, âWhat they really want is prints of your tits and my ass.â
But people who knew Marilyn, especially when she was attending The Actors Studio, often remark on how deliberately she could âturn onâ the Marilyn persona and turn it off again. With such an incredible ability to project her personality, she could be sitting unnoticed one minute and then make âMarilynâ appear and take center stage just with posture, attitude and facial expression. She may not have known exactly how she was able to do this â so much of personality is innate and instinctive â but she could definitely do it on purpose.
Which was a major factor in making her such an incredible model.
As sexy as she could be, Marilyn was also capable of coming across as innocent and childlike, a woman men want to take care of.
Unfortunately, many who are chameleon-like and able to assume so many guises so easily have trouble being themselves when not on stage. Like Zelig as played by Woody Allen. Or like Peter Sellers the way so many describe him. Certainly a psychologist might suspect that growing up as an orphan and foster child Norma Jeane might well have become desperate to find ways to find acceptance and be notices. Perhaps even with an excessive reliance on sexuality. And it seems likely the word âdesperateâ might well describe why Marilyn was always so uncomfortable with success and relationships, was so needy and unreliable both personally and professionally and tended to question both her intellectual and acting ability.
Marilyn Monroe by Philippe Halsman
Marilyn Monroe by Gordon Parks
Marilyn Monroe by Richard Avedon
But one place she apparently never questioned her ability nor felt uncomfortable was in front of a still camera. The camera loved her and she loved the camera. And that relationship resulted in thousands of photos of Norma Jeane/Marilyn that continue to appeal to generations of fans and have made her one the most iconic of all celebrities of the modern age.
Marilyn Monroe is everybodyâs amour.
Marilyn Monroe photographed by close friend and collaborator Milton Greene.
Marilyn Monroe by Bert Stern

Bill Dobbins is a pro photographer located in the Westwood area of Los Angeles. He is a veteran photographer and videographer who has published eight books, including two fine art photo books:
The Women: Photographs of The Top Female Bodybuilders (Artisan)
Modern Amazons (Tashen)

Marilyn Monroe being photographed by Cecil Beaton. Many actors dislike sitting for still photos, try to avoid this and are uncomfortable during the sessions. Marilyn loved posing for stills and her energy and enthusiasm help to create so many wonderful images.
Ah, the glamour of a movie star! Marilyn by George Barris.

Bill Dobbins is a photographer, writer and videographer located in Los Angeles, CA. Bill is highly experienced as a commercial and advertising photographer, and is particularly noted as "The Body Photographer" for his physical portraits of fit, athletic physiques - particularly those of female athletes. Bill was also the Founded Editor of Flex Magazine, and has co-authored 3 books with Arnold Schwarzenegger. View all posts by billdobbins

Week 15: From My Vault: 3 Movies Watched
August 1, 2018 Kathy Bugajsky From My Vault, General Entertainment, Movies, Recommendations Leave a comment
Continuing my weekly series where I go through my impressively large collection (1,054 titles) of DVDs and Blu-Rays. I have been neglecting older movies for new ones, so Iâm going through and re-watching everything from my vault. I have the films divided into categories: General, Series, Classics, Kids, Shakespeare, and Documentary. Iâm starting with General.
The Brothers Grimm (2005)
Format: DVD Special Features: Behind the scenes, commentary, and interviews
Last Time Watched: Over ten years ago
Originally Viewed: Theater
Comments After Re-Watching: The special effects donât hold up. This was the first movie I saw Lena Headey in. Although, I didnât learn her name until the next year when she was in 300.
Why You Should You Watch This: A great cast tells a different version of the events of how the brothers Grimm collected all their fairytales.
Bull Durham (1988)
Format: DVD Special Features: Behind the scenes, commentary, and interviews
Last Time Watched: Over ten years ago
Originally Viewed: Rental
Comments After Re-Watching: This movie holds up well, and everyone in it looks so young. You may notice that on the âAbout the Authorâ tab of my blog, the quote is a variation on the speech Kevin Costner makes in this movie.
Why You Should You Watch This: Whether you are a baseball fan or not, this is full romantic-comedy is a fun watch.
Cabin in the Woods (2012)
Format: Blu-ray Special Features: Behind the scenes, commentary, and interviews
Last Time Watched: Within the last year
Originally Viewed: Theater (3 times)
Comments After Re-Watching: Drew Goddard and Joss Whedon are just the best.
Why You Should You Watch This: This is a horror film like Scream is a horror film. While they have the same elements, it pays homage to those movies rather than being one and adding a comedic twist.
Another weekâs selection with more randomness of the types of movies I own. Come back next week to see what I watched next.
Have you seen any of these movies? Let us know your thoughts in the comment section!

Merrill Kelly, maybe the oldest rookie in baseball, takes a unique path from Korea to MLB
Jeff Passan
MLB columnist
Yahoo Sports December 5, 2018, 4:10 PM GMT
Merrill Kelly signed a two-year contract worth a guaranteed $5.5 million with the Arizona Diamondbacks on Tuesday. (Getty Images)
Merrill Kelly left the United States because he feared he never would get to play Major League Baseball. Now, heâs ready to be the oldest rookie in the game â and one of the best stories, too.
The 30-year-old Kelly, who has spent the last four years pitching in Korea, signed a two-year contract worth a guaranteed $5.5 million with the Arizona Diamondbacks on Tuesday, sources familiar with the deal told Yahoo Sports. Arizona later confirmed the signing, which will pay the right-hander $2 million this season, $3 million in 2020 and includes a $4.25 million team option for the 2021 season with a $500,000 buyout and a buyout-free $5.25 million club option for 2022.
Scroll to continue with content
Ad
Welcome home, @Mert_723! The #Dbacks have agreed to terms with right-handed pitcher Merrill Kelly on a two-year contract through 2020, with club options for the 2021 and 2022 seasons.
Kelly grew up in Scottsdale and attended Desert Mountain High School, Yavapai College and @ASU. pic.twitter.com/nJvNQAB7lC
â Arizona Diamondbacks (@Dbacks) December 5, 2018
Story continues
Kellyâs ascent to the major leagues, and likely into the Diamondbacksâ rotation, is unprecedented. Never before has a player with zero major league experience played in Korea and returned directly to MLB. In 2016, reliever Tony Barnette came back from Japan to make his big-league debut at 32 with the Texas Rangers. And Eric Thames â who, like Kelly, is represented by Sosnick, Cobbe & Karon â parlayed an MVP season in Korea into another shot in the major leagues with a guaranteed three years and $15 million in Milwaukee.
Often players who find their major league prospects stunted or even nonexistent will turn to jobs in Asia, where they can experience success and riches that go well beyond what the best Triple-A players can earn. Journeyman Dennis Sarfate became the most dominant closer in Japan and received a three-year extension worth more than $18 million, adding to the well over $10 million he already had made. Two of Sosnick, Cobbe & Karonâs other clients, Randy Messenger and Kris Johnson, each signed $10 million deals, a hefty haul in Nippon Professional Baseball. Kelly was well on his way to that.
An eighth-round pick out of Arizona State in 2010, Kelly was stagnating in the Tampa Bay Raysâ organization after 2014, his fourth full season. He had thrown well, posting a 2.76 ERA, but SK Wyverns, a perennial power in the KBO, was willing to offer Kelly the opportunity the Rays couldnât.
While his numbers in Korea look pedestrian â a career 3.86 ERA, including 4.13 in 2018 â they come in a cartoonishly inflated offensive environment. Scouts left Kellyâs starts impressed with his variety of pitches and particularly his ability to throw deep into games, with 729 2/3 innings over the last four seasons.
Once he won a championship with SK Wyverns and their manager, former Royals skipper Trey Hillman, Kelly wanted to see what the major league market would bear. The answer was: plenty. The World Series champion Boston Red Sox were interested. So were the up-and-coming San Diego Padres. Kellyâs desire to return to his hometown â he was born and raised in the Phoenix area â and Arizonaâs willingness to guarantee a second year sealed the homecoming.
In the world of relief pitchers who make well over $5 million a year, Kelly could prove a solid bargain â perhaps not on the level of Miles Mikolas, who returned from Japan last year to dominate for the St. Louis Cardinals, but a back-of-the-rotation type that every team covets. And thatâs fine with him. Every pitch Merrill Kelly throws in the big leagues, after all, heâs making history.

â¢ Team owner pays nearly $100K in Walmart layaway charges
â¢ Ex-NFL star going to prison for attempted murder
â¢ 49ersâ long snapper suspended for second PED violation

Campbell Newman sacks outspoken Assistant Health Minister Chris Davis, calling his position 'untenable' - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)

Campbell Newman sacks outspoken Assistant Health Minister Chris Davis, calling his position 'untenable'
By Melinda Howells
Updated May 14, 2014 07:07:44
Photo: Chris Davis says he paid the price for speaking out and not maintaining Cabinet solidarity. (ABC News - file image)
Map: Brisbane 4000
Queensland Premier Campbell Newman has sacked his Assistant Health Minister Chris Davis for criticising State Government policies.
Dr Davis is a former Australian Medical Association state president and first-term MP for Stafford.
He first clashed with his own party over contracts for senior doctors, but in the past few weeks he has also publicly questioned proposed changes to the Crime and Misconduct Commission (CMC).
Dr Davis commissioned a poll of his electorate and threatened to cross the floor and vote against the legislation.
He ultimately did not cross the floor, saying he was happy with amendments put forward by the Attorney-General.
But on Tuesday afternoon Mr Newman said Dr Davis's position was "untenable".
"[His] recent actions have breached the long-established Westminster convention of Cabinet solidarity," Mr Newman said in a statement.
"I thank Dr Davis for the contribution he has made in the role, and look forward to his continuing contribution to the Government's efforts on behalf of his constituents."
Dr Davis said he has paid the price for speaking out, and that was the reality.
Queensland Opposition Leader Annastacia Palaszczuk says the sacking of Dr Davis showed Mr Newman does not tolerate criticism.
"It's very sneaky for the Premier to sack this Assistant Health Minister an hour before the [federal] budget is delivered," she said.
"It shows how weak the Premier is and it also shows that this Premier, Campbell Newman, will not tolerate anyone else's views other than his own."
Treasurer Tim Nicholls has defended the timing of the announcement.
"I was in Townsville yesterday, only returned back to Brisbane at about 11:30 today. The Premier had a series of engagements. The earliest date that we could meet and the earliest time was later this afternoon," he said.
"It was done as soon as we possibly could after reviewing the week's events on Monday."
Topics: state-parliament, liberal-national-party, brisbane-4000
First posted May 13, 2014 18:32:22

A Better Deposition Dealing with Problem Witnesses and Difficult Attorneys
Course Description
AK
1.50 Credit Hours

A Better Deposition Dealing with Problem Witnesses and Difficult Attorneys
AK
1.50 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Litigation, Personal Injury 
Original Production Date: 09/11/2015
Run Time: 1:30:07
AK Course Exp: 09/11/2020   
If you are a trial attorney you have inevitably been forced to deal with difficult witnesses and hostile attorneys at some point in your legal career. Problem witnesses can take many forms - the dishonest witness, the evasive witness, the hostile witness- the witness that doesn't remember what they had for breakfast. All too often, witnesses try to frustrate the discovery process - and depositions in particular - by their obstructive and abusive behavior. And we all have stories about hostile or bullying opposing counsel.
This CLE course examines strategies to effectively depose some common difficult witnesses and also provides tips on how to deal with difficult attorneys during the deposition process. Join trial attorney Roy Comer as he discusses the hostile witness, the basics of questioning, dealing with the problem witness, the forgetful or unsure witness, the dishonest witness and the obstructing lawyer. Further topics covered by Mr. Comer include controlling the deposition, what doesn't work, the goal of the deposition, the form of questioning, the 4 step process for dealing with the evasive witness, videotaping depositions, looking for visual clues, asking more, quickening the pace, the Duty of Candor, the bullying lawyer, the law is your friend, talking to the witness, the improperly objecting attorney, the lawyer that wants to go off the record all the time, the condescending lawyer and the "I'll fix it later lawyer."
For over thirty-five years Roy L. Comer has been dedicated to handling damage cases, including catastrophic personal injury and wrongful death cases arising from automobile, truck, motorcycle, medical negligence, defective products, and dangerous premises claims. In addition, Mr. Comer has represented individuals and medium-sized businesses in real estate, landlord-tenant, insurance and contract disputes. Defending these types of claims has provided Mr. Comer with further insight into how insurance companies approach these claims. Mr. Comer's clients depend on his broad experience, coupled with the highest legal, professional and emphatic standards.
offered in:
Alaska | Arizona | California | Connecticut | District of Columbia | Florida | Georgia | Idaho | Illinois | Maryland | Massachusetts | Michigan | Missouri | New Jersey | New York | North Dakota | Pennsylvania | South Dakota | Washington    
A Better Deposition: Person Most Qualified (PMQ) Depositions
Course Description
AK
1.25 Credit Hours   
Streaming Video
Audio Download

Add To Cart
Ã
A Better Deposition: Person Most Qualified (PMQ) Depositions
AK
1.25 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Business Law, Employment Law, Litigation    
Original Production Date: 09/23/2016
Run Time: 1:15:13
AK Course Exp: 09/23/2021   
The person most qualified (PMQ) deposition is a powerful discovery tool or - or a headache of a lifetime - depending what side of the litigation you're on. Whether you are pursuing remedies against a business entity or defending a corporation, how you plan and prepare for the PMQ deposition will ultimately determine the success you achieve for your client. With all of the possible traps, do you know how to effectively take, defend, and prepare for the PMQ deposition?
In this CLE course, veteran civil litigator Roy Comer provides practical tips and advice for your next PMQ deposition. When you complete this course you will know how to: indentify what makes a person most qualified, prepare the notice, respond & object to the notice, select the PMQ witness, prepare the PMQ witness, prepare the testimony, take the deposition, spot common traps and defend the PMQ deposition. Deposing the person most qualified is drastically different than the standard lay witness deposition and since party admissions are admissible against the company or entity, PMQ depositions can produce valuable testimony that can greatly aid settlement or sway the jury at trial.
For over 30 years Roy L. Comer has been dedicated to handling damage cases, including catastrophic personal injury and wrongful death cases arising from automobile, truck, motorcycle, medical negligence, defective products, and dangerous premises claims.
offered in:
Alaska | Arizona | California | Colorado | Connecticut | District of Columbia | Florida | Georgia | Illinois | Maryland | Massachusetts | Michigan | Missouri | Nevada | New Hampshire | New Jersey | New York | North Dakota | Oregon | Pennsylvania | South Dakota | Washington

Course Description
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
Streaming Video
Audio Download

A Lawyer's Refresher: Financial Records & Financial Statements
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Litigation  
Original Production Date: 04/24/2014
Run Time: 1:02:56
AK Course Exp: 12/31/2019   
Many types of attorneys need to understand the basics of how to read a financial statement - from criminal law attorneys to family law practitioners. However, we are attorneys and not accountants, so it's not always easy to understand where to look and how to break down the important financial information in your case.
If you need help in this area join forensic accountants Richard Holstrom and Joshua Vannetti for an attorney's refresher on financial records and financial statements. The main subjects covered include using financial data to tell the story, understanding the various forms of financial statements and the use of income statements in analysis. Further topics addressed include accounting language, the different forms of financial statements, accounting basics, accrual accounting, cash basis accounting, accounting systems, the accounting process, the purposes of financial statements, published financials, types of financial information & statements, the balance sheet, income statement data & sources, the statement of shareholder's equity, statement of cash flows, other sources of financial information, what to ask for and the "so what" moment.
Richard Holstrom currently works at RGL Forensics and has been involved in the field of Forensic Accounting exclusively since 1980. He has worked extensively with insurance companies and attorneys focusing his career on forensic accounting, measurement of damages and litigation support. Mr. Holstrom has been designated as an accounting expert in State Courts of California and Nevada and Federal Courts in California, Arizona and Hawaii. He has provided expert testimony in both depositions and at trial in excess of 100 times in the past 10 years. Joshua Vannetti also works at RGL Forensics and specializes in litigation support and claims evaluation. He has worked with attorneys and insurance professionals by performing damage calculations for disputes involving breach of contract, business interruption, employee dishonesty, and similar matters of economic loss. Mr. Vannetti's previous background in financial institutions lends itself well to forensic accounting as he understands what records are available at the financial institution level, and knows what to look for related to negotiable instrument fraud and embezzlement.

A Litigators Advice on How to Keep Your Clients Out of the Courtroom
Course Description
AK
1.25 Credit Hours   
Streaming Video
Audio Download

Ã
A Litigators Advice on How to Keep Your Clients Out of the Courtroom
AK
1.25 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Bankruptcy, Business Law, Employment Law, Immigration Law, Litigation   
Original Production Date: 03/20/2015
Run Time: 1:15:00
AK Course Exp: 03/20/2020   
If you can help to keep your clients stay out of court, clients will look to you as a trusted legal advisor that they can turn to for proactive legal advice and counseling - and not just the person to call once they've been sued. Transactional attorneys, nonprofit attorneys and in-house counsel can definitely benefit from this proposition by knowing the key facets of their client's businesses and making sure their legal liabilities are accounted for and properly addressed. Even immigration attorneys with international clients can serve as a valuable resource to clients coming to America on investor visas by assisting with their client's with basic counseling on starting and running a business.
In this course Miami business attorney Brett Trembly highlights a number of practical and legal points that you can advise your business clients on to help you serve as a valuable resource and keep them out of court. Brett starts by presenting ten general tips to advise your business clients on, lists four key documents that your clients must have in place, analyzes five essential terms for every contract and closes by highlighting key nonprofit issues. Further subjects covered include: business formation & structure, keeping good records, business insurance, appropriate security protections, vendors, employee handbooks, being proactive, independent contractor agreements, the articles of organization, the operating or shareholders agreement, client or service contracts, emergency plan documents, terms of service, prevailing party attorneys? fees, forum & venue selection clauses and termination & damages clauses.
Brett Trembly started the Trembly Law Firm over four years ago to work with business owners to resolve their legal issues as quickly, painlessly, and cost-effectively as possible. In the South Florida legal community, Brett sits on the Board of the South Miami Kendall Bar Association, the Florida Bar 11th Circuit Grievance Committee, volunteers on the Florida Bar Young Lawyers Division Mentoring Program, the Dade-County Bar Associations Rainmakers Committee, and annually volunteers for Miami-Dade County's Ethical Governance Day. Brett also maintains his leadership emphasis and is strongly committed to giving back, serving as Past President of the Rotary Club of South Miami, President of B.N.I. Superior, Vice-President of the Rotary Foundation of South Miami, Inc., and is a proud member of the Chamber South and Pinecrest and Palmetto Bay Business Associations.

A Practical Approach to 1031 Exchanges
Course Description
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
Streaming Video
Audio Download
Video Download
Preview Course
$24.99  
Add To Cart
Ã
A Practical Approach to 1031 Exchanges
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Real Property, Taxation 
Original Production Date: 01/26/2017
Run Time: 1:00:55
AK Course Exp: 01/26/2022   
Even the most lucrative sale of investment property includes one major downside - taxes. But what if you don't sell the property and you exchange it instead? A properly structured 1031 exchange allows an investor to sell an investment property and reinvest the proceeds in a new property while deferring all capital gains taxes. But like anything having to do with the tax code, properly structuring and completing a 1031 exchange is an incredibly complex process wrought with pitfalls.
This CLE course provides practitioners with a comprehensive review of IRC 1031 tax deferred exchanges and the real estate transactions that utilize this tax deferral strategy. A 1031 expert, attorney J. Paul Spring will mainly cover the history of 1031 tax deferred exchanges, the reasons for employing IRC 1031 and key requirements when structuring the 1031 exchange. This course will also address the following topics: the Starker Exchange, key benefits of the 1031 exchange, REITs, 1031 investment property converted to a primary residence, exceptions, the like kind requirement, leases & options, types of 1031 exchanges, sales contract language, the equal or greater value requirement, flipping properties, the timing of transactions, identifying the replacement property, related properties and reverse exchanges. In addition to discussing the legal requirements of the 1031 exchange, Mr. Spring also discusses number practical considerations that arise in these complex transactions.
Mr. Spring has been a practicing attorney in California for more than thirty years, specializing in real estate, title insurance, business law, tax-deferred exchanges, trust law and short-sale transactions. He is currently the President of Investment Capital Resources.
offered in:
Alaska | Arizona | California | Connecticut | District of Columbia | Florida | Georgia | Illinois | Maryland | Massachusetts | Michigan | Missouri | Nevada | New Hampshire | New Jersey | New York | North Dakota | Oregon | Pennsylvania | South Dakota | Texas | Washington  
A Primer on European Patent Practice
Course Description

1.25 Credit Hours

A Primer on European Patent Practice
AK
1.25 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Business Law, Intellectual Property 
Original Production Date: 10/18/2017
Run Time: 1:15:24
AK Course Exp: 10/18/2022   
Entrepreneurs and inventors often come up with great ideas that they think will be the next great product at home in the United States and around the world. But patenting that Green Bay Packer cheese head beer coolie hat in Germany might not be the best idea - no matter how great your client thinks it will sell.
In this CLE program, Eric Hanscom and Greg Sach highlight key legal and practical points about seeking patent protection in the EU. Eric and Greg will mainly discuss the U.S. patent system, the EU patent system and common pitfalls when seeking patent protection in the EU. Additional subjects covered: the three types of U.S. patents, provisional patent applications in the U.S. & Europe, comparing the cost of U.S. vs. European patents, popular validations in Europe, the unitary patent, typical EPO examination procedures, costs & timelines, added subject matter, intermediate generalizations, novelty & the two categories of prior art, the inventive step, patent ineligible subject matter, methods for treatment and the number of claims.
Eric Hanscom is actively involved in overseeing litigation, contract negotiation and customs issues around the globe over matters ranging from patent and trademark infringement to breach of contract. With over 14 years of experience in the patent profession, Greg Sach has expertise in drafting, prosecution and appeal proceedings for the European Patent Office and he also handles patent applications before the UK and Germany.

A Sport's Lawyers Guide to Working with Athlete Clients
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Business Law, Criminal Law, Family Law, Sports and Entertainment, Trusts and Estates    
Original Production Date: 08/28/2015
Run Time: 1:01:22
AK Course Exp: 08/08/2020   
The issues that professional athletes face on a daily basis are very unique compared to the rest of society because athletes have a different career length and economic situation than most people. In addition, professional athletes have a different mindset than the average person when it comes to dealing with business and personal issues. This presentation is for sports law lawyers, estate planning attorneys, criminal defense attorneys, family lawyers and any other lawyer that is looking to assist and counsel with athlete clients.
To learn more about representing athlete clients join attorney and sports agent Brandon Leopoldus as he introduces you to the mindset of the professional athlete, helps you as an attorney provide increased value to your athlete clients and discusses how you can give the best possible service to your athlete clients. The main topics addressed include 12 key stats & insights about professional athlete clients, knowing the client's mindset, understanding the client's needs, coaching your athlete client and building your team. Additional issues presented include invincibility, trusting without reason, rewarding risk, collecting solutions, focusing on the result, keeping your quarterback safe, making your athlete client part of the team, being a lawyer - not a fan, being yourself and finding your niche. This presentation is for sports law lawyers, estate planning attorneys, criminal defense attorneys, family lawyers and any other lawyer that is looking to assist and counsel with athlete clients.
After completing a career as a minor league baseball umpire, Brandon Leopoldus worked in the front office of the Mountain Collegiate Baseball League as the Director of Baseball Operations, before attending Thomas Jefferson School of Law and working for Mandalay Sports. An attorney, mediator and sports agent, Brandon works with his clients' teams of agents, managers, accountants, and other professionals to craft unique legal strategies to safeguard the client's assets and interests. He focuses on developing the best legal game plan for his clients while keeping their information in confidence, with respect, and confidentially.

A Tangled Web: Ethical Issues Created by Your Online Legal Content
Course Description
AK
1.25 Credit Hours
1.25 Legal Ethics
Streaming Video
Audio Download
Video Download
Preview Course
$31.24  
Add To Cart
Ã
A Tangled Web: Ethical Issues Created by Your Online Legal Content
AK
1.25 Credit Hours   
1.25 Legal Ethics
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Specialty Areas: Legal Ethics
Practice Areas: Ethics  
Original Production Date: 09/15/2015
Run Time: 1:15:30
AK Course Exp: 09/15/2020   
If you're like many attorneys and firms, you utilize numerous online resources to provide legal information to the public and advertise your services to potential clients. However, while numerous firms and attorneys rely on websites and social media to grow their businesses, some don't give a second thought to the fact that their online activities could run afoul of the ethical rules. Facebook, Twitter, Quora, AVVO, LinkedIn, law firm websites and other social media platforms all pose significant ethical risks for lawyers who may be inappropriately or even inadvertently advertising to or soliciting clients.
In this course, attorney Ken Matejka points out the ethical issues created by your online content and shows you how to fulfill your ethical duties when advertising and offering legal information on your law firm website, social media websites and other online resources like LinkedIn and Yelp. The five main topics that Ken discusses include false & misleading communications, solicitations, required disclaimers, privacy policies and eliciting online reviews. Further issues covered in this course include legal information/legal advice, case results, specialists, guarantees, establishing the attorney-client relationship online, online Q & A websites, contingency fees & costs, ABA Formal Opinion No. 10-457, recommended elements for a valid disclaimer, recommended placement for disclaimers, unencrypted email and the attorney-client privilege and the integrity of the profession.
Ken Matejka, President, LegalPPC, Inc., Internet Services for the Legal Profession Ken Matejka is a California attorney and a former member of the American Bar Association's Standing Committee on Lawyer Referral and Information Services. For seventeen years, he worked at the Lawyer Referral and Information Service of the Bar Association of San Francisco and in 2006, co-founded LegalPPC, an Internet Services Company dedicated to helping lawyers and lawyer referral services get more clients from Google. Ken has been a regular presenter at events like the ABA's Annual LRIS Workshop and for attorneys across California on the topic of online visibility and lead generation for the solo practitioner's law practice. LegalPPC currently provides Internet services to about 20 bar associations and a large number of law firms nationwide.
offered in:
Alaska | Arizona | California | Connecticut | District of Columbia | Florida | Georgia | Illinois | Maryland | Massachusetts | Michigan | New Jersey | New York | North Dakota | Pennsylvania | South Dakota | Washington   
Accounts Receivable Management for Lawyers
Course Description
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
Streaming Video
Audio Download

Almost every business must deal with slow paying clients and delinquent accounts - law firms are no exception. However, as professionals some attorneys are hesitant and timid when it comes to collecting fees that are owed by clients. To ensure a continuous and timely revenue stream, law firms need to establish accounts receivable policies & procedures and all attorneys at the firm need to adhere to these policies. Yet, many attorneys and firms fail to adopt and follow these vital policies & procedures for accounts receivable when running their law practices.
In this practical and informative CLE course Robert Weinberg will provide you with tips and best practices so you can manage your account receivables with professional discipline. The main topics discussed include the patterns repeated by professionals, dealing with your emotions, setting up policies & procedures, establishing a firm-wide methodology that works, withdrawal from representation and deciding whether to sue the client for fees. Mr. Weinberg also has a section in the course dedicated to collecting the judgment. Further subjects covered include taking the soft approach to collecting fees, setting client expectations, retainers & evergreen retainers, the special client, terminating the client, charging interest on past due monies, contractual arbitration in the engagement letter, creating liens, locating debtor assets, the writ of execution, wage garnishment, seizing property and settlement. Mr. Weinberg provides specific strategies to help you overhaul your business practices and make the collection process run more smoothly.
An A-V rated attorney, Robert A. Weinberg specializes in debtor-creditor matters and consults with business and professional firms on AR management. He has been practicing debt collection and accounts receivable management for over 25 years and he represents business owners & professionals in helping establish sound policies to better ensure fewer delinquent accounts. Mr. Weinberg also provides collection services when customers or clients refuse to pay. His law practice is located in Encino, California.

In a recent case, a U.S. Magistrate Judge sanctioned an attorney for telling opposing counsel it wasnât âbecoming of a womanâ to raise her voice during a contentious deposition. Yes, we have made strides when it comes to creating a level playing field for women in the legal professionâ¦ but there is still a long way to go.

Advanced Asset Protection Planning
Course Description
AK
2.00 Credit Hours   
Streaming Video

Advanced Asset Protection Planning
AK
2.00 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Litigation, Personal Injury, Real Property, Trusts and Estates  
Original Production Date: 09/19/2014
Run Time: 2:00:45
AK Course Exp: 09/19/2019   
For the past several years, asset protection has been one of the fastest growing areas of law. Asset protection is also one of the most controversial because the goal is to shield assets from the reach of creditors. Asset protection should simply be about structuring the ownership of one's assets to safeguard them from potential future risks. Most asset protection structures are commonly used business and estate planning tools - such as limited liability companies, family limited partnerships, trusts and the like. Properly implemented asset protection planning should be legal and ethical. It should not be based on hiding assets or on secrecy. It is not a means or an excuse to avoid or evade U. S. taxes. There is no one "magic bullet" in asset protection and the term "asset protection" encompasses a number of planning and structuring mechanisms that may be implemented by a practitioner to minimize a client's exposure to risk.
For each client the asset protection solution will be different, depending on the identity of the debtor, the nature of the claim, the identity of the creditor and the nature of the assets. These are four threshold factors that are either expressly or implicitly analyzed in each asset protection case. The analysis of these four factors determines what planning would be possible and effective for a specific client. Join Jacob Stein as he discusses these factors and more in this highly informative and practical CLE course on advanced asset protection planning. The main topics discussed include the goal of asset protection planning, specific asset protection structures and assets that are commonly protected. Further issues addressed include the "Home Depot" method, hiding assets, the debtor's examination, principle asset protection structures, proactive vs. reactive asset protection planning, retirement plans, ERISA, life insurance, fraudulent transfer laws, the intent test, constructive fraud, the attorney's liability, transferring assets between spouses, common law & community property states, LLCs, piercing the corporate veil, types of assets, the living trust, revocable & irrevocable trusts, the trust protector, key clauses in the trust, offshore structures, liquid assets, protecting businesses, the personal residence, the equity strip and additional asset protection structures.
Mr. Stein is one of the nation's leading experts on asset protection and is one of California's best-known attorneys, teaching dozens of legal seminars each year on the subjects of asset protection and advanced tax planning. He is a Certified Tax Law Specialist and is AV rated by Martindale-Hubbell. Mr. Stein is the author of numerous articles on asset protection and tax planning, and is the author of Asset Protection Planning (Education Foundation, 2009) and Advanced Tax Planning Techniques (Education Foundation, 2009). He is an adjunct professor of taxation at the CSU, Northridge Graduate Tax Program, and has been an instructor with the California CPA Education Foundation and National Business Institute for many years. He is also a frequent guest speaker at various Bar, Estate Planning Council and CPA group meetings. Mr. Stein is admitted to practice in California and before the United States Tax Court.
offered in:
Alaska | Arizona | California | Connecticut | District of Columbia | Illinois | Maryland | Massachusetts | Michigan | Missouri | New Jersey | New York | North Dakota | Pennsylvania | South Dakota 
Advanced Planning with Trusts
Course Description
AK
2.00 Credit Hours

Advanced Planning with Trusts
AK
2.00 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Litigation, Personal Injury, Real Property, Trusts and Estates  
Original Production Date: 09/18/2014
Run Time: 2:00:03
AK Course Exp: 09/18/2019   
The goal of all asset protection planning is to insulate assets from claims of creditors without concealment or tax evasion. It is usually impossible to completely and absolutely protect assets, and the focus is on making assets more difficult and more expensive to reach. All asset protection planning is based on two principle premises: creditors can generally reach any asset owned by a debtor, and creditors cannot reach those assets that the debtor does not own. In this obvious dichotomy, trusts come to the rescue by splitting the beneficial enjoyment of trust assets from their legal ownership. This is the main reason that trusts are widely used in asset protection. Not all types of trusts are effective asset protection devices, but a properly drafted and structured trust may be an almost impregnable form of asset protection.
If you would like to learn more about how trusts are used in advanced asset planning and protection please join Jacob Stein as he provides a thorough and practical overview of this important topic. Mr. Stein mainly discusses trusts, specific planning areas, asset protection planning, the use of trusts in asset protection and special needs planning. Further issues discussed include the limitations of trusts, ownership of trusts, key elements of a trust, revocable vs. irrevocable trusts, trust protectors, dealing with real estate, where to set up the trust, estate tax planning, AB Trusts, life insurance trusts, Intentionally Defective Grantor Trust (IDGT), Qualified Personal Residence Trust (QPRT), the goal of asset protection, the ?Home Depot? method of asset protection, insulating assets, fraudulent transfers, the Intent Test, trusts & asset protection, tax consequences, foreign trusts, choice of law, and needs-based government benefits.
Mr. Stein is one of the nation's leading experts on asset protection and is one of California?s best-known attorneys, teaching dozens of legal seminars each year on the subjects of asset protection and advanced tax planning. He is a Certified Tax Law Specialist and is AV rated by Martindale-Hubbell. Mr. Stein is the author of numerous articles on asset protection and tax planning, and is the author of Asset Protection Planning (Education Foundation, 2009) and Advanced Tax Planning Techniques (Education Foundation, 2009). He is an adjunct professor of taxation at the CSU, Northridge Graduate Tax Program, and has been an instructor with the California CPA Education Foundation and National Business Institute for many years. He is also a frequent guest speaker at various Bar, Estate Planning Council and CPA group meetings. Mr. Stein is admitted to practice in California and before the United States Tax Court.

Alaska | Arizona | California | Connecticut | District of Columbia | Illinois | Maryland | Massachusetts | Michigan | New Jersey | New York | North Dakota | Pennsylvania | South Dakota

An Attorney's Duty: Competence & Substance Abuse
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
1.00 Legal Ethics
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Specialty Areas: Legal Ethics
Practice Areas: Competence Issues, Ethics, Professionalism, Substance Abuse 
Original Production Date: 01/13/2016
Run Time: 1:01:26
AK Course Exp: 01/13/2021   
Substance abuse and depression are two of the main contributors that affect an attorney's competence to practice law and lead to high rates of suicide among lawyers. Attorneys are nearly twice as likely to have problems with drugs & alcohol and are nearly four times more likely to suffer from depression when compared to the general population. In fact, the depression rate in the legal profession is the highest among all professions and over 50% of all discipline cases involve an underlying substance abuse issue.
In this course, Richard P. Carlton presents an overview of the connection between substance abuse, depression and an attorney's competence to practice law. The main topics discussed include the law as a high risk profession, substance abuse & depression disorders, personality traits of attorneys, methods to cope with the stress & the mental challenges of the legal profession and managing the expectations of clients. Further issues presented and discussed include brain chemistry, depression, traits of pre-law students & the effects of law school, lawyers as pessimists, thinking like a lawyer, resources & assistance for attorneys, the stress response, negativity bias, fear & negativity, mindfulness, the pace of life for attorneys and time shifting.
Richard P. Carlton, MPH, is the Acting Director of the Lawyer Assistance Program (LAP) of the State Bar of California and has been addressing mental health and disability concerns in the legal profession for over twenty-five years. He frequently delivers continuing legal education (CLE) presentations on addressing substance abuse and managing stress to bar associations, State Bar sections and law firms throughout California. In addition to his work with the LAP program of the State Bar of California he is also a consultant to the U.S. Courts for the Ninth Circuit, the National Conference of Bankruptcy Judges and the Idaho Judicial Branch on matters of judicial stress and wellness.

An Epidemic Among Lawyers: Depression, Substance Abuse, and Suicide
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
1.00 Legal Ethics
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Specialty Areas: Legal Ethics
Practice Areas: Competence Issues, Ethics, Substance Abuse  
Original Production Date: 01/15/2014
Run Time: 1:02:14
AK Course Exp: 12/31/2019   
Substance abuse and mental health in the legal profession have recently been in the headlines - and for good reason. Substance abuse and addiction are two of the primary health concerns in the United States and the concern is even greater in the legal profession. The National Institute on Alcohol and Alcohol Abuse (NIAAA) estimates that 10% of the U.S. population is alcoholic or chemically dependent and the abuse may be as high as 20% in the legal profession. Since substance abuse and addiction often leads to mental health issues, it's not surprising that suicide is the third leading cause of death amongst lawyers after cancer and heart disease.
Join Susan Brown as she provides insight about the epidemic of substance abuse, addiction and suicide in the legal profession. The main issues covered include the stressors that contribute to depression, addiction & suicide in the legal profession, the symptom profiles of depression, PTSD & substance abuse, the signs of addiction, where to get help and how to get help. Further issues addressed include the "culture" of the legal profession, the result of stressors, perfectionism, DSM-V symptoms of depression, symptoms of secondary traumatic stress, "the solution," alcohol & other substances, CAGE screening, addictive thinking, consequences of addiction in the legal profession, "real lawyers don't ask for help," suggested solutions, the Lawyer Assistance Program (LAP), the "Other Bar," Lawyers Helping Lawyers and using EMDR therapy for trauma & addiction treatment.
Susan Brown is a Licensed Clinical Social Worker (LCSW) and Board Certified Diplomate (BCD). She has been in private practice in La Mesa, California, since 1987 and her areas of expertise include Post Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD), mood disorders, substance and behavioral addictions, and marriage counseling. Mrs. Brown specializes in a treatment approach called EMDR (Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing) developed by psychologist Francine Shapiro, Ph.D., in 1989. She is a Certified Approved Consultant through the EMDR International Association. EMDR is an efficient, effective, and extensively researched therapy for clearing out and resolving negative traumas. She is often called in by attorneys to work with clients that have suffered severe trauma.

An Introduction to Patent Prior Art Research
AK
1.00 Credit Hours   
Media Options:
Streaming Video
| Audio Download
| Video Download
Add To Cart
Practice Areas: Business Law, Intellectual Property 
Original Production Date: 06/03/2016
Run Time: 1:00:35
AK Course Exp: 06/03/2021   
For patent prosecution, patent prior art research is an essential requirement and one of the critical first steps in the prosecution process. Prior art research should be concluded early on in the process before time and money are expended on the construction of the patent and the application. Prior art research will identify those patent publications that may prevent the innovation in question from being patented and can provide a type of road map in the early stages of development that can assist in providing work arounds of the prior art that will allow the innovation to be patented or used freely in the market.
In this CLE course Intellectual Property attorneys Alan Kendrick and Eric Hanscom provide an excellent practical discussion about the best practices when conducing a patent prior art search. Alan and Eric mainly address the main goal, types & scope of prior art research and patent publication prior art research. Additional topics covered: patent prosecution, freedom to operate, FTO Research, state of the art research, patentability search, invalidity research, patent landscape research, whitespace analysis, non-patent publication research, discussions with the inventor, strategy development, qualifying terms, searching by number/date ranges, searching by applicant/assignee name or by inventor name, searching by specific data fields and using Patbase.
Before beginning his own practice Eric Hanscom utilized his science background and law degree to gain experience in multiple facets of patent, trademark and copyright law and the application of those property rights. He has been actively involved in overseeing litigation, contract negotiation and customs issues in the US, Asia, Europe, South American and Australia over matters ranging from patent and trademark infringement to breach of contract. Alan Kendrick has been an attorney since 1998 and his practice focuses on intellectual property matters including patent, trademark, copyright, trade secret and unfair competition. He has several years of experience providing patentability and invalidity research in a wide variety of disciplines including aerospace, mechanical, industrial, energy, medical, materials, food technology and the automotive arts.

Practice Areas: Business Law, Law Practice Management, Taxation 
Original Production Date: 03/11/2016
Run Time: 1:45:00
AK Course Exp: 03/11/2021   
When you are a child you are scared of the boogeyman or the monster under the bed. When you are an adult, you are scared of the IRS. One of the worst days in the life of a person or small business owner is when the IRS undertakes collection activities to collect past due taxes. Because of their wide powers and ability to freeze and seize assets, IRS collection activities can have a devastating impact on an individual taxpayer or small business' financial operations.
Presented by tax attorney Sam Brotman, this CLE program will provide the non-tax practitioner with a practical guide to the process and timeline of IRS collections. Sam mainly discusses how a filed return becomes a balance due, how the IRS Automated Collection Systems works, dealing with Revenue Officers and how to best resolve IRS collection issues for your clients. Further issues discussed include the benefits of understanding the IRS collections process, an overview of IRS examinations & audits, how attorneys get audited, balance due notices, liens, levies & wage garnishments, revenue officer specific collection actions, 120 day extensions, the statute of limitations, running, financial hardship, installment agreements, offers in compromise, defeating IRS liens and levies and bankruptcy.
Samuel D. Brotman is the founder of Brotman Law. His practice primarily centers on all aspects of tax litigation and criminal/civil tax controversies in front of the Internal Revenue Service, Franchise Tax Board, Employment Development Department, Board of Equalization, and various other state/local tax agencies. Although a strong proponent of early stage tax resolution, Sam's practice is uniquely tailored to assist clients in all phases of their tax controversy from administrative resolution to suits in superior/district court. In addition, Sam frequently handles corporate/real estate/litigation matters related to small and mid-size businesses.

Christianity/ Devotionals / Living Free Every Day / Living Free - May. 2, 2011

Living Free - May. 2, 2011
Living Free Every DayÂ®
Bury Things Dead
Today's Scripture
"Be kind and compassionate to one another, forgiving each other, just as in Christ God forgave you." Ephesians 4:32 NIV
Thoughts for Today
Forgiving one another is crucial to the success of marriage and family relationships. Forgiveness means that family members do not allow anger to grow, hold grudges, or keep a record of misdeeds. Forgiveness can open up a whole new perspective on life.
Forgiveness is an act of God's grace. Today's scripture directs us to forgive each other; just as in Christ God forgave us. God extended His grace to us. We can't earn His forgiveness it is a gift. Jesus paid the price for our sins; we receive forgiveness by accepting Him as our Lord and Savior. God wants us to forgive others the same way. Not because they deserve it, but because of our love for our Lord and our gratitude for His forgiveness.
Sometimes forgiveness is difficult, but God will help us. We are dependent on His grace both to give and to receive forgiveness.
Consider this â¦
Dr. Steve Bradshaw of Bryan College in Dayton, Tennessee, often says that things that are buried dead stay buried but things that are buried alive come back to haunt us. Forgiveness helps us bury things dead. Forgiveness is not forgetting. It is choosing to remember the past in a way that does not affect the present in a toxic way. To forgive means to turn loose, release, or remit.
Have you buried anything alive? Offenses buried alive will fester and grow into bitterness. Someday they will come out, often in an ugly way. If you are carrying an offense from your spouseâor someone elseâit's time to dig it up. Ask God to help you forgive, and then bury it dead.
Prayer
Father, I know I've been carrying this resentment. Please forgive meâand help me to forgive. In Jesus name...
These thoughts were drawn from â¦
Committed Couples: God's Plan for Marriage & the Family by Dr. Jimmy Ray Lee. Whether in a private or group setting, couples will be encouraged spiritually and romantically as they research biblical principles that affirm their vows. This book can help every married couple grow spiritually and emotionally in their relationship. It is also a great help for engaged-to-be-married couples.
Would you like to have these devotions appear daily on your church or ministry website? Learn More

The Facility
Where it All Happens.
The facility has 6 retractable 40-50 foot cages and an area devoted specifically to strength and conditioning training. One cage is equipped with a pitching machine while another cage is wired for videotaping the playerâs swing in order to better evaluate the playerâs development. There is a safe viewing area for parents as well. Ample parking for everybody.

Posts for tag: hygiene
Traveling Tips
By Dr. Michelle Kim
July 15, 2015
Category: Uncategorized
Tags: hygiene Traveling
Summer means travel for many people in the United States. July especially is a month full of vacations and sun! Whether your plans call for a day trip to your lake house, a weekend the Dells or a fun Bahamas getaway, we want to make sure everyone takes care of themselves while theyâre having summer fun.
Here are a few travel hygiene tips while youâre playing in the sun this July:
1. Keep in mind that public places like airplanes and hotels may be quite germy!
Consider traveling with sanitizing wipes to clean off those plane seats. A disinfecting spray to use in your hotel shower and toilet can prevent the possible spread of fungi, bacteria and viruses.
2. Donât go barefoot!
We've seen many cases of athlete's foot and plantar warts from patients walking barefoot so be sure to keep a pair of sandals handy to wear in all public places, including your hotel room and pool areas.
2. Always keep hand sanitizer with you!
Shield yourself from germs while traveling by keeping a travel-sized bottle of hand sanitizer with you. The best kind is an alcohol-based hand sanitizers in gel form like Purell. Also, it is extremely important to wash your hands before eating and after using the bathroom.
4. Ditch the flip-flops and sandals!
When youâre going on hikes or tours and choose gym shoes instead. Not only will this keep your feet from getting dirty, but you will be more comfortable and give your feet better support throughout the day whether youâre walking around sight-seeing, hiking, or shopping!
0 Comment(s) Permalink
Traveling Tips
By Michelle Kim
May 15, 2014
Category: travel hygiene
Tags: DM Foot and Ankle Associates Dr. Diana Emini Dr. Michelle Kim Lemont Illinois podiatrist hygiene sandals flip-flops travel tips sneakers hand washing hand sanitizer
Memorial Day is almost here and summer is on its way â warm-weather blockbusters such as âThe Amazing Spider-Man 2â are already in theaters, and will soon be followed by the highly anticipated âGodzilla.â
Summer means travel for many people in Lemont. Whether your plans call for a day trip to the upcoming Taste of Chicago, a weekend in Wisconsin Dells or a getaway out-of-state, as podiatrists at DM Foot and Ankle Associates, Dr. Diana Emini and I want to make sure everyone takes care of themselves while theyâre having summer fun.
Here are a few tips for travel hygiene when youâre playing in the sun this summer.
1. Keep in mind that airplanes and hotels are public places, and they may be quite germy! Consider traveling with sanitizing wipes to clean off those plane seats. A disinfecting spray to use in your hotel shower and toilet can prevent the possible spread of fungi, bacteria and viruses. In our office, we carry Citrace, a hospital-grade disinfectant that smells citrusy. Also, it's best to avoid walking barefoot around the hotel. We've seen many cases of athlete's foot and plantar warts from patients walking barefoot in public.
2. While in transit or spending the day in the hot sun, try wearing polyester "dry-fit" shirts that are lightweight, wrinkle-free and dry quickly. As a bonus -- they take up almost zero room in a backpack or suitcase. Stores such as REI also sell varieties of wrinkle-free clothing, including pants and button-down shirts. Itâs also a good idea to keep a stain-erasing pen, such as Tide to Go, in your purse or backpack. On days when you've been sweating, remember to wash your feet and let them air out once you're back at your hotel.
3. Shield yourself from germs while traveling by keeping a travel-sized bottle of hand sanitizer with you. The Centers for Disease control and Prevention recommends ethanol alcohol-based hand sanitizers in gel form that are at least 60 percent ethanol. Also, donât forget to wash your hands before eating and after using the bathroom. Always wash with hot, soapy water. Be generous with the soap and rub your hands together for 20 seconds before rinsing.
4. Ditch the flip-flops and sandals when youâre going on hikes or tours and choose sneakers instead. Not only will this keep your feet from getting dirty, but you will be more comfortable and give your feet better support throughout the day.
By Michelle Kim
0 Comment(s) Permalink
MRSA infects NFL players
By Diana Emini
October 23, 2013
Category: foot infections
Tags: DM Foot and Ankle Associates Dr. Diana Emini Dr. Michelle Kim Lemont Illinois foot doctor foot infections MRSA hygiene ingrown nails
The Chicago Bears have the week off this Sunday, but did you know that three players on another NFL team â the Tampa Bay Buccaneers â have been sidelined and made news in recent weeks for infections that began in their feet?
Three Bucs players have been diagnosed with MRSA. The list includes: lineman Carl Nicks, cornerback Johnthan Banks, and Lawrence Tynes, who was diagnosed in August.
NFL.com reported that Nicks missed the first two games of the season, then returned to the field before an infection came back in his left foot. Meanwhile, cbsnews.com reported, Tynes was sidelined with an ingrown toenail when he was diagnosed with MRSA.
MRSA, or methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus, is sometimes called a âsuper bugâ because this strain of bacteria has become resistant to most antibiotics.
Here are some facts about the bacteria, commonly referred to as âstaph infections,â from webmd.com:
Â· Plenty of healthy people carry regular âstaphâ without being infected by it â 25 to 30 percent of the population has staph bacteria in their nose.
Â· Staph can become a problem if it gets into the body, usually through a cut. Once there, it can cause an infection.
Â· Staph is one of the most common causes of skin infections nationwide. Most of the time, these are minor and don't need special treatment. Less often, staph can cause serious issues such as infected wounds or pneumonia.
The Centers for Disease Control reports the risk of infection can be increased with activities that involve crowding, skin-to-skin contact and sharing equipment. Folks such as athletes, students, members of the military in barracks may be at higher risk.
This kind of skin infection can be spread through contact with an infected wound, such as showers or sharing towels, razors that touched infected skin.
Due to unnecessary overuse of antibiotics (such as taking antibiotics for a viral infection such as a cold,) or people not finishing the complete course of antibiotics, bacteria such as staph can mutate and become resistant to them. MRSA is staph on steroids â standard penicillin and other types of antibiotics cannot kill it off. When this happens, strong antibiotics may need to be infused through the veins, and the infected site may need to be surgically drained. Left untreated, this bacteria can invade deeper into tissue and may pose a serious health risk.
As podiatrists, Dr. Michelle Kim and Dr. Diana Emini suspect that walking barefoot in the locker room may have caused the spread of this nasty bug among the Bucs players. Lesson learned: Always wear shower shoes in public such as the pool or the gym! If you suspect you have any sort of foot infection -- an ingrown nail, a wart, or fungus â call DM Foot & Ankle Associates for an evaluation.
By Diana Emini

MLB Player Profile: Rick Porcello - Fantrax
Rick Porcello #22 SP Boston Red Sox
Close
IP
The Boston Red Sox are openly listening to trade offers for starting pitcher Rick Porcello as they try to clear salary space for bullpen help. Rivals also insist that Boston is willing to talk about shortstop Xander Bogaerts and outfielder Jackie Bradley. Porcello isn't the sexiest fantasy starter, but he put up 17 wins in 2018 a year after taking 17 losses. He also posted a career-high 8.9 K/9 in 33 starts and had a decent 4.28 ERA for the World Series champs. The difference in 2017 was that he allowed a career-high 38 home runs. The right-hander won 22 games for Boston in 2016, so staying in Beantown would be best for his fantasy value.
Rick Porcello To Start Game 3 Of World Series
Oct. 25, 2018
More from
.Boston Red Sox manager Alex Cora said that starting pitcher Rick Porcello will start Game 3 of the World Series in Los Angeles against the Dodgers on Friday. Nathan Eovaldi won't be available to start until at least Game 4 after tossing two innings in relief in each of the first two games. Porcello won 17 games this year but was a bit inconsistent and allowed four earned runs and seven hits in his lone start in the ALCS against the Astros. The Dodgers are much more dangerous against right-handed pitchers as well, although Porcello was better on the road (3.86 ERA, 1.26 WHIP, 9.4 K/9) than at home (4.77 ERA, 1.07 WHIP, 8.4 K/9). In two career starts at Dodger Stadium, Porcello has a 5.91 ERA with seven runs allowed in 10 2/3 innings. He'll be on a short leash on Friday.
Porcello gave up four runs on seven hits with one walk over four innings in a no-decision against...
Oct. 18, 2018
Porcello gave up four runs on seven hits with one walk over four innings in a no-decision against the Astros in Game 4 of the American League Championship Series. He struck out three.
Analysis available to registered users
Rick Porcello To Start Game 4 Of ALCS
Oct. 16, 2018
More from
.Boston Red Sox starting pitcher Rick Porcello will start Game 4 of the American League Championship Series against the Astros in Houston on Wednesday. Porcello has been effective out of the bullpen for short stints this postseason, and he also held the Yankees to one run on four hits in five innings in Game 4 of the Division Series. He faced the Astros twice in the regular season and had a 4.50 ERA, 1.25 WHIP and 8.3 K/9 over 12 innings. Still, starting him on the road against a potent offense will be a risk for DFS owners.
Porcello will start Game 4 of the ALCS against the Astros on Wednesday, Hunter Atkins of the...
Oct. 16, 2018
Porcello will start Game 4 of the ALCS against the Astros on Wednesday, Hunter Atkins of the Houston Chronicle reports.

Rick Porcello Unlikely To Be Available For Game 3 Of ALDS
Oct. 6, 2018
More from
.Boston Red Sox starting pitcher Rick Porcello threw a bullpen session before Game 1 of the American League Division Series against the Yankees on Friday and entered the game in relief in the eighth inning, so he likely will be unavailable to pitch in Game 3 of the series. That means the Red Sox might have to move up expected Game 4 starter, Nathan Eovaldi, to Game 3 in New York. Porcello had 17 wins this year but was up and down with a 4.28 ERA, 1.18 WHIP and 190 strikeouts in 191 1/3 innings in 2018. The home run ball has been the issue for him, as he allowed a league-high 38 in 33 starts last year and 27 in 33 starts this year. Porcello could go in a potential Game 4 (if necessary). He actually had success against New York in four starts against them this year with a 2.31 ERA, but he'd be a risky DFS pick in the Bronx.

The 29-year-old has a strong 16-7 record on the season, but that is mainly because the Red Sox offense is talented enough to bail him out when he struggles. He has a decent matchup against the New York Mets on Saturday, but who knows what version of Porcello will be on the mound.

Rick Porcello To Get Extra Rest Soon
Sep. 4, 2018
More from
Boston Red Sox starting pitcher Rick Porcello will make his next start on Sunday and will then see extended rest as the team begins to align their rotation for the playoffs. Porcello allowed one run on just two hits in five innings for a win over the Braves on Tuesday, and he's now 16-7 with a 4.20 ERA and 9.12 K/9 on the season over 29 starts. He's had his ups and downs for fantasy owners, though, but the 16 wins are nice. He may only make a start or two the rest of the way before October.
Rick Porcello Rebounds On Tuesday
Sep. 4, 2018
More from
Boston Red Sox starter Rick Porcello allowed one run on two hits through five innings in Tuesday's 5-1 win over the Atlanta Braves. Porcello struck out five batters while walking one en route to his 16th win of the season. This was a nice bounce-back performance from the 29-year-old, as Porcello had a 5.11 ERA through six starts in August. He remains a core piece of the Red Sox rotation and is a good source of wins, although his ratios can sometimes be a bit troublesome. Red Sox manager Alex Cora also mentioned that after Porcello's start against the Houston Astros on Sunday, he will be given some extra rest. Those managers that need to roll the dice can start Porcello against the defending World Series champs, but it seems like a good time to leave him on the fantasy bench.
Rick Porcello Tosses Another Ineffective Outing
Aug. 30, 2018
More from
Boston Red Sox starter Rick Porcello allowed four runs on eight hits through five innings on Thursday against the Chicago White Sox. He also had seven strikeouts and three walks. Luckily, his offense bailed him out and gave him a no-decision as the Red Sox came back to win 9-4. Porcello has simply not been trustworthy lately, as he now has an inflated 5.90 ERA through his last nine starts. He still has a fantastic 15-7 record for the season, but that is more indicative of the team he plays for than how well he has pitched. While it is fairly premature to consider dropping Porcello, he definitely is not inspiring much confidence lately. He should probably be sat his next time out against the formidable Atlanta Braves.

Rick Porcello Has Another Inadequate Outing
Aug. 20, 2018
More from
Boston Red Sox starter Rick Porcello was saddled with the loss on Monday night against the Cleveland Indians. Porcello went seven innings, allowing five runs on six hits (three of which were home runs). Porcello has been wildly inconsistent over his past seven starts. In three of those games, he has allowed one run or less. In the other four, he has allowed a total of 24 runs. That basically serves as a synopsis for Porcello's season as he can range from dominant to downright terrible. He is still in the SP3/SP4 range for fantasy purposes, but he is prone to blowing up. It may be best to play the matchup game with Porcello until he strings together some consistently good outings.

Rick Porcello Has Tough Conditions To Get Sixth Win
May. 19, 2018
More from
Boston Red Sox starting pitcher Rick Porcello has an uphill battle to obtain his sixth win of the season Saturday. First, he takes the mound against the Orioles, a team that has a career .290 batting average against him. In 18 starts, Porcello is 4-11 with a 4.88 ERA and 1.31 WHIP against Baltimore. Second, he does not historically do well in the confines of Fenway Park, where he has a 4.30 ERA and 1.26 WHIP to go with a .297 batting average against. However, he is 2-1 with a 3.54 ERA in 2018. If you are one to forego any risks at all, Saturday might be a day to give Porcello a rest.

Bent Creek
Tucked in an irregular area south and east of 164th and Blondo Street is Bent Creek, a popular family neighborhood of two story and ranch homes priced in the low to mid $200,000âs. Most homes in the development were constructed in the early 1990âs and now display mature landscaping. Entrances to the community and other public spaces are beautifully planted and maintained by the Landscaping Committee of the Bent Creek Homeownerâs Association.
This committee is only one of several, which actively function for the communityâs well-being through the Association. Another plans social events which encourage fun and provide opportunities to meet other residents--an Easter Egg Hunt, a 4th of July Bike Parade, and an all-inclusive Fall Festival. The Architectural Committee reviews plans for exterior home additions and remodeling, and monitors the area for covenant compliance. Other committees organize clean-up days, plan the all-community garage sale, and up-date the neighborhood directory, e-mail addresses and the Web site. The sense of community abounds!
Several highly rated Millard elementary schools are in close proximity to the area as are a Millard middle school and high school. Bent Creek is home to an eleven acre park with a playground and picnic area, and a bike and hiking trail runs along the western edge of the community. Several swimming pools and public and private golf clubs are a short drive away as are baseball and soccer fields.
Village Pointe (a large shopping center with numerous specialty shops, clothing stores, restaurants, bars and a multiplex movie theater) is near-by and smaller strip centers with grocery stores are only a short distance from Bent Creek. With easy access to the West Dodge Expressway, offices, a medical center, and other places of employment are close at hand.
For further information about this family friendly neighborhood contact www.bentcreekomaha.org
